{
  "text": "From the diagnosis results shown in Table 3 , compared with the method in [CITATION_1] , it can be seen that when R 1 is in each faulty state the method in this paper makes some progress in diagnosis. 1. When R 1 =1\u2126 and the others element's parameter is changing under their influence of tolerance randomly, the circuit is without fault. The method in [CITATION_2] is unable to determine the real state of the circuit. To such state, the diagnosis ratio using the method in this paper can attain 90%. 2. Seen from the property of the diagnosis results, the method in this paper is a quantitative diagnosis and it can roughly estimate the parameter perturbation. Meanwhile the method in [CITATION_3] is a qualitative diagnosis and it only locates the faulty element. 3. From the compared result in the example, when the parameter change is minor, the diagnosis ratio of method in [CITATION_4] is better. When the parameter change is larger, the diagnosis ratio of method in [CITATION_5] is descending heavily. But, to all those faults in the CUT, the diagnosis ratio of the method proposed in this paper is high and steady. 4. In all misdiagnosis using the method in this paper, the non-faulty element is diagnosed wrongly as faulty one but the faulty element is not lost. But, in all misdiagnosis using the method given in [CITATION_6] , the non-faulty element is diagnosed wrongly as a faulty one and the faulty element is lost.",
  "citation_candidates": [
    "3049401",
    "38940902",
